body:
We came across this problem while writing a wrapper class for our database connections. We had a private $pdo variable containing an instance of the PDO class. Once we created the following  __destruct() function, all asserts (AssertTrue, AssertEqual, etc.) passed, even if they shouldn't have.

Here is the important part of the code:
<code>
class DatabaseConnection
{
    private $pdo;
    public function __construct($connectionString, $user, $password)
    {
        try
        {
            $this->pdo = new PDO($connectionString, $user, $password);
            $this->pdo->setAttribute(PDO::ATTR_AUTOCOMMIT, true);
        }
        catch(PDOException $e){ }
    }

```
public function __destruct()
{
    try
    {
        $this->pdo->rollBack();
    }
    catch(PDOException $e) {}      
}
```

}
</code>

Than after 
<code>
$connection=new DatabaseConnection($this->dbcon, $this->dbuser, $this->dbpasswd);
</code>
in a test 
<code>
$this->AssertFalse(true);
</code>
will not cause the test to fail. 

Any ideas what could cause the problem?
